EXECUTION VERSION
Facilities Service Agreement
entered into between
LAKE IRIS SOLAR, LLC
and
ITC ENERGY SOLUTIONS LLC
PUBLIC VERSIONFacilities Service Agreement
This Facilities Service Agreement (“Service Agreement”) dated this 23rd day of January,
2025, is entered into by and between LAKE IRIS SOLAR, LLC a limited liability company
organized under the laws of the State of Delaware (“LIS”), and ITC ENERGY SOLUTIONS LLC,
a limited liability company organized under the laws of the State of Michigan (“ITCES”) to
compensate ITCES for (i) ITCES’s design, engineering, and construction of certain facilities, as
described herein, for LIS’s exclusive use, and (ii) certain services provided to LIS by ITCES for
the facilities through ITCES’s ownership and operation of such facilities, as further described
below. ITCES and LIS are each referred to herein as “Party,” and collectively as “Parties.”
WHEREAS, the Parties have entered into that certain “Lake Iris Project Term Sheet” dated
January 20, 2023, pursuant to which ITCES would obtain right-of-way easements to construct,
own and operate a generation tie line and other facilities (“Gen-Tie Facilities”) and described in
further detail below and further identified in Exhibit A) on behalf of LIS; and,
WHEREAS, ITCES has successfully obtained the right-of-way easements to support the
construction, ownership, maintenance, and operation of the Gen-Tie Facilities; and
WHEREAS, in accordance with this Agreement, LIS will pay ITCES for its capital
investment in, and ownership, operation, and maintenance of, the Gen-Tie Facilities as set forth in
Exhibit B.
NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing mutual promises and covenants
hereinafter set forth and other good and valuable consideration, and intending to be legally bound
hereby, the Parties hereby agree to the following terms and conditions:
I. CONSTRUCTION, OPERATION, AND MAINTENANCE OF GEN-TIE
FACILITIES
(a) ITCES will obtain right-of-way easements and design, engineer, procure
equipment with respect to, and construct the Gen-Tie Facilities (“Construction Work”), which is
herein defined as an approximate 0.50 miles of 120 kV (single circuit) generation tie-line
(including but not limited to associated assets, disconnect, other equipment, real property,
documentation, permits, and any other materials necessary to facilitate the construction and
operation of the Gen-Tie Facilities) to be interconnected, starting at the International Transmission
Company (“ITCT”) owned Greenwood Substation and ending at LIS Generation Facility located
in the Township of Greenwood, Michigan, in accordance with the requirements of the Generation
Interconnection Agreement dated December 9, 2022 (“GIA”) executed between the Midcontinent
Independent System Operator, Inc. (“MISO”), LIS, and ITCT.
(b) ITCES will construct the Gen-Tie Facilities, either through itself, one of its
affiliate companies, and/or one of its engineering, procurement and construction contractors (each,
an “EPC ITCES”) using “Good Utility Practice” which is herein defined to mean any of the
practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility
industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the
exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made,
PUBLIC VERSIONcould have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with
good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to
be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes
all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region. In furtherance of the
construction, ITCES, will achieve the following milestones by the dates indicated (each, a
“Milestone Date”):
(i) complete the design and engineering of the Gen-Tie Facilities on or
prior to June 1, 2024 (or such later date as may be agreed to by the Parties pursuant to a written
amendment to this Agreement);
(ii) commence construction of the Gen-Tie Facilities between May 12,
2025 and October 31, 2025 (or such later date as may be agreed to by the Parties pursuant to a
written amendment to this Agreement);
(iii) achieve Operational status of the Gen-Tie Facilities on or prior to
December 31, 2025 (or such later date as may be agreed to by the Parties pursuant to a written
amendment to this Agreement). For the purposes of this Agreement, the term “Operational” shall
mean commercial operation of the generation tie line to enable LIS to wheel power onto the ITCT
transmission grid.
No changes to the Milestone Dates are permitted unless approved by the parties in writing.
(c) During the Construction Work and the subsequent operation and
maintenance of the Gen-Tie Facilities by ITCES:
(i) upon reasonable prior notice to ITCES, LIS will have the right to
gain supervised access to the Gen-Tie Facilities (1) to observe construction and attend progress
meetings for construction of the Gen-Tie Facilities, (2) to observe operation and maintenance of
the Gen-Tie Facilities, and (3) to conduct inspections of the Gen-Tie Facilities at mutually
acceptable times; provided, however, that LIS’s access and inspection rights will be at its sole risk,
including the risk of its employees and consultants making said inspection;
(ii) LIS will have no right to direct any of the Construction Work or
operation and maintenance work performed by ITCES, its affiliates, or the EPC ITCES or any
subcontractor or supplier unless otherwise agreed upon by the Parties in writing. LIS will not
materially interfere with any such construction or operation and maintenance, and LIS will observe
all reasonable rules and procedures provided to LIS in writing that are promulgated by ITCES, any
of its affiliates, or the EPC ITCES, and LIS will promptly repair any damage which it causes to
any portion of the construction work resulting from its access to and inspection of such work;
(iii) ITCES will keep LIS advised periodically, but no less frequently
than monthly, as to the progress of its design of the Gen-Tie Facilities and/or of any service
disruptions or outages of the Gen-Tie Facilities during the operation and maintenance of the Gen-
Tie Facilities by ITCES;
PUBLIC VERSION(iv) ITCES will keep LIS advised periodically, but no less frequently
than monthly, as to the progress of its design, procurement and construction efforts with respect to
the Gen-Tie Facilities, and to the subsequent testing, operation, maintenance, and repair of such
Gen-Tie Facilities;
(v) if any phase of the engineering, equipment procurement, or
construction of the Gen-Tie Facilities do not (1) meet the standards and specifications of ITCES,
(2) the standards of LIS around interconnection voltage, reliability, transmission capacity, and
other reasonable specifications provided to ITCES by LIS, and (3) Good Utility Practice
(collectively, the “Construction Specifications”), ITCES will remedy such deficiencies in that
portion of the Line as promptly as possible after ITCES becomes aware of such deficiencies.
(d) ITCES will provide, obtain and maintain, or cause to be provided, obtained
and maintained, a commercial liability insurance policy with respect to the Gen-Tie Facilities; and
(e) ITCES, through itself, its affiliates, and EPC ITCES, will obtain and
provide, and be solely responsible for, all workers compensation and other mandatory insurance
applicable to its employees.
(f) In addition, ITCES will:
(i) file the Facilities Service Agreement with FERC (as defined below)
no later than 90 days prior to the Gen-Tie Facilities becoming Operational; and
(ii) create with ITCT an Operating Interconnection Procedure –
External Entity Interface document to govern the operation interface between the Gen-Tie
Facilities and ITCT’s transmission network.
(g) LIS shall obtain and maintain the insurance to the satisfaction of ITCES in
the event that it (or its employees and/or agents) accesses the Gen-Tie Facilities pursuant to this
Service Agreement.
(h) All Construction Work performed by ITCES under this Service Agreement
shall be in accordance with the Construction Specifications and all laws, statutes, orders, decrees,
injunctions, licenses, permits, approvals, agreements and regulations of any federal, state, local or
other governmental regulatory or administrative agency, court, commission, department, board, or
other governmental subdivision, instrumentality, legislature, rulemaking board, tribunal,
arbitration body, or other governmental entity, including the FERC (“Governmental Authority”)
having jurisdiction over the matter in question which are applicable to or which affect ITCES’s
provision of the Construction Work and/or the O&M Services (as defined below) (collectively,
“Applicable Laws”). Additionally, ITCES shall provide all labor and services of personnel
necessary to complete the Construction Work in accordance with the Construction Specifications
and Applicable Laws.
II. EFFECTIVE DATE AND INITIAL TERM
The effective date of this Service Agreement (“Effective Date”) will be as dated above,
PUBLIC VERSIONor, in the event that this Service Agreement must be reviewed and approved by the Federal Energy
Regulatory Commission (“Commission” or “FERC”), such other later date as it is permitted to
become effective by the Commission. This Service Agreement will continue for the earlier of: (a)
35 (thirty-five) years from declaration of commercial operation of the LIS generating facility under
the J1331 generator interconnection agreement; or (b) until all payments governed by this Service
Agreement have been collected by ITCES (“Initial Term”).
III. GEN-TIE SERVICE
ITCES will own, operate and maintain the Gen-Tie Facilities for LIS’s sole and exclusive
use, and, during the Initial Term, and any subsequent term(s), will also provide LIS with operation,
maintenance, repair, modification and/or replacement services for the Gen-Tie Facilities
(including services for all equipment, fixtures and other tangible personal property related thereto)
requested by LIS during the Initial Term of this Agreement; and/or (b) such other services that are
agreed to by the Parties to be provided pursuant hereto (collectively, the “O&M Services”).
ITCES agrees that all Services will be performed in accordance with Good Utility Practice and in
compliance with all Applicable Laws. ITCES agrees to notify LIS upon discovery of any known
or suspected deficiency in any Services provided under this Service Agreement. ITCES agrees
that all O&M Services pursuant to this Service Agreement shall be performed safely and without
injury to any person or damage to any property. ITCES agrees to inspect all equipment and
supplies used in performing O&M Services pursuant to this Service Agreement to ascertain the
equipment’s and supplies’ safety and fitness for such use and to render such equipment and
supplies safe for such use before using such equipment or supplies. LIS shall have the right to
inspect any of ITCES’s equipment and supplies used in performing O&M Services under this
Service Agreement at any time during the Initial Term of this Agreement (and any subsequent
terms, if applicable). ITCES shall be responsible for obtaining all required permits and
certifications to complete the O&M Services contemplated by this Service Agreement.
ITCES warrants that any O&M Services performed under this Service Agreement shall be
performed by properly skilled personnel in accordance with this Service Agreement and Good
Utility Practice. The sole liability of ITCES for defective products, materials or O&M Services
provided pursuant to Good Utility Practice under this warranty, shall be limited to repairing or
replacing any such product or materials at the cost of LIS (except where reimbursed by a
manufacturer’s warranty in which case, for the avoidance of doubt, LIS will be entitled to the
proceeds from any such warranty.) The liability of ITCES for services performed to a standard
of performance less than Good Utility Practice shall be the re-performing any such services on
the same conditions as the original O&M Services at the cost of ITCES and/or its
subcontractors. The foregoing is LIS’s exclusive remedy and, EXCEPT AS EXPRESSLY
STATED HEREIN, THERE ARE NO OTHER WARRANTIES, EXPRESSED, IMPLIED OR
STATUTORY, INCLUDING THE WARRANTY OF MERCHANTABILITY OR FITNESS
FOR ANY PURPOSE. In the case of a defective manufactured product or material, ITCES shall
take all commercially reasonable actions to make claim on such warranty on behalf of LIS.
Subject to any modification by FERC (as further set forth below), this Service Agreement
provides LIS with sole and exclusive access to and use of 100% of the Gen-Tie Facilities and its
energy transmission capacity, and the O&M Services hereunder will be provided by ITCES for
the Gen-Tie Facilities only.
LIS acknowledges that ITCES does not convey to LIS any right to electric transmission
PUBLIC VERSIONservice on the interconnecting transmission owner’s transmission system or any service covered
under the tariff of the interconnecting transmission owner or the GIA. LIS will separately obtain
transmission service from the interconnecting transmission owner.
ITCES will provide all information to LIS for its regulatory compliance (including, but not
limited to, North American Electric Reliability Corporation (NERC), FERC, and Midcontinent
Independent System Operator (MISO) obligations associated with the GIA, Gen-Tie Facilities and
this Service Agreement). LIS will be the registered Generator Owner (GO)/Generator Operator
(GOP) and responsible for all NERC compliance obligations, including penalties, as well as being
responsible for “Transmission Owner’s Interconnection Facilities” (TOIF), as per the GIA.
With respect to the operating practices and procedures for the LIS generator and the Gen-
Tie Facilities, the Parties shall comply with the Operating Interconnection Procedure – External
Entity Interface.
IV. TERMINATION OPTION
The Parties may mutually agree to extend this Service Agreement by written amendment.
In the event LIS desires to extend this Service Agreement, then one hundred and eighty (180) days
prior to the expiration of the Initial Term (or as soon as practicable thereafter and prior the
expiration of the Initial Term), the Parties shall negotiate, in good faith, the terms on which such
extension of the Initial Term shall be made; provided, further, notwithstanding anything to the
contrary herein, the Initial Term shall be automatically extended, and this Services Agreement
shall remain in full force and effect, during the course of such good faith negotiations between the
Parties.
In the event the Parties do not agree to an extension of the Agreement, then LIS will
reimburse ITCES for any unreimbursed expenses allowed under this Service Agreement, if any,
and ITCES will have the right to either continue ownership of the Gen-Tie Facilities in place, or
to remove them and restore the underlying right-of-way at the expense of LIS. In the case that
ITCES removes the Gen-Tie Facilities, LIS will be invoiced and pay for the costs of removal and
restoration of the right-of-way. All real estate rights associated with the Gen-Tie Facilities (i.e.,
underlying rights of way and/or easements) will remain with ITCES.
LIS will continue to make payments as set forth in this Service Agreement until the
negotiations between the Parties relating to the transaction structure of the purchase of the Gen-
Tie Facilities by LIS are complete; and at such time, this Service Agreement will terminate.
V. FACILITIES SERVICE CHARGE
Upon the Gen-Tie Facilities having been placed in service (“In-Service Date”), and then
continuing annually on the Effective Date anniversary throughout the Initial Term of this Service
Agreement, ITCES will invoice to LIS (the “Invoice”), and LIS will make a payment to ITCES,
the minimum charge as set forth under the “Estimated Annual Facilities Payment(s)” set forth in
Exhibit B, in addition to any direct charge expenses incurred by the Gen-Tie Facilities (i.e.,
expenses directly assessed to the Gen-Tie Facilities, including but not limited to, the O&M
PUBLIC VERSIONServices, special inspections, equipment replacements, taxes, special assessments, permits, fees,
etc.). Direct expenses shall be clearly itemized and supported with backup expense documentation
by ITCES to the reasonable satisfaction of LIS if such direct expenses are outside of the Estimated
Annual Facilities Payment.
For the O&M Services, LIS shall pay ITCES for labor, materials, equipment, sales taxes,
administrative and general expenses as well as all other expenses resulting from the performance
of this Agreement. Beginning on the one-year anniversary date from the Effective Date and
thereafter, on an annual basis, ITCES will submit an invoice to LIS. The payment of the
undisputed amount set forth in each invoice shall be due within thirty (30) days after receipt by
LIS of any such invoice. Such charges will be without markup unless agreed to by the Parties in
writing.
VI. SECURITY
(a) LIS will provide ITCES with security in the form of either (i) an irrevocable
Letter of Credit, (ii) a parent guarantee from NorthStar Clean Energy Company or other entity
acceptable to ITCES (“PG”), or (iii) another form of security acceptable to ITCES and/or issued
by a Bank rated “A-” or higher by Standard & Poor’s or A3 or higher by Moody’s in an amount
equal to $ 1,160,000.00 USD (the “Security”). The Security will be provided to ITCES by LIS
pursuant to this Article VI(a) within fifteen (15) calendar days of the execution of this Service
Agreement by all Parties.
(b) Security will remain in place until expiration of this Service Agreement,
however the underlying Security may be reduced concurrent with the amortization of the
remaining Total Capital of the Gen-Tie Facilities and on an annual basis, LIS may obtain the
amortized Total Capital figure from ITCES. Any fees or costs associated with the provision of
Security are the responsibility of LIS. Any Security provided by LIS must be kept active, must
continue to meet ITCES’s Security requirements and must be available to ITCES for the purpose
of making the Invoices under this Service Agreement in the event that LIS fails to make such
payment when due and payable and has not been paid in full within thirty (30) days of such
payment being due under this Service Agreement and after written notification from ITCES to LIS
that such payment is overdue.
(c) In the event LIS fails to make a Payment by the Due Date and such breach
is not cured as noted below in Section VII(a), ITCES will be entitled to draw on the Security posted
by LIS in the amount of missed Payments, as well as any accrued interest charges based on the
Commission’s regulations at 18 C.F.R § 35.19a. If LIS fails to make an Invoice payment by the
applicable due date and Security has been depleted due to withdrawal for Invoices, LIS will
provide ITCES with new irrevocable security, in a form reasonably acceptable to ITCES (“New
Security”) within thirty (30) days of ITCES’s written demand for New Security.
VII. BREACH, DEFAULT AND CROSS-DEFAULT
(a) General: Upon a breach under this Service Agreement, the non-breaching
Party or Parties will give written notice of such breach to the breaching Party. The breaching Party
PUBLIC VERSIONwill have thirty (30) calendar days from receipt of the notice of breach within which to cure such
breach; provided if cured within such time, the breach specified in such notice will be deemed
cured and treated by the Parties as if it had not occurred. If a breach is not cured as provided in
this Section VII(a.) or is not capable of being cured within the period provided for herein, the
breaching Party will be in default under this Service Agreement, in which case the Parties will
proceed as set forth below.
(b) LIS Default: LIS will be in default of this Service Agreement if LIS: (i) is
more than thirty (30) calendar days late in paying an undisputed Invoice or Annual Payment;
provided that ITCES has given LIS notice of and LIS has failed to cure such late payments
consistent with Section VII(a.); (ii) fails to provide New Security within thirty (30) calendar days
of ITCES’s demand for New Security; (iii) terminates operation of its LIS Generating Facility
prior to the end of the Initial Term (including any subsequent term(s), if applicable) of this Service
Agreement; or (iv) is declared to be in default under its GIA. In the event of a default, LIS will
promptly pay to ITCES all remaining payments under this Service Agreement. In the event that
LIS does not promptly pay all amounts due and owing to the ITCES, the ITCES may draw on the
remaining balance of the Security provided by the LIS. This payment or draw on the Security does
not limit any and all rights and remedies available to the ITCES allowed by law with respect to
such default or collecting all amounts owed for the remaining months due under this Service
Agreement. LIS will indemnify ITCES for reasonable costs, attorney fees and/or expenses
incurred with respect to a default or collecting all amounts owed for the remaining months under
this Service Agreement.
(c) ITCES Default: ITCES will be in default of this Service Agreement if it:
(i) fails to complete the Construction Work in accordance with this Service Agreement; (ii) fails
to meet its obligations to provide the O&M Services as set forth in Article II; (iii) fails to comply
in any material respect with any term, provision, or covenant of ITCES set forth under this Service
Agreement; or (iv) fails to maintain required insurance under this Service Agreement, provided
that consistent with Section VII(a.), LIS has given ITCES notice of and ITCES has failed to cure
such breach with Section VII(a.) In the event of a default, consistent with the GIA, Good Utility
Practice, and this Service Agreement, LIS may take whatever actions or inactions with regard to
the Gen-Tie Facilities in order to (i) preserve public health and safety, (ii) preserve the reliability
of its generation facilities associated with this Service Agreement, (iii) limit or prevent damage,
and/or (iv) expedite restoration of service, including termination of this Service Agreement. In
addition to terminating this Service Agreement, LIS shall be entitled, upon occurrence of any event
described in this Section VII(c), to pursue all remedies available at law, at equity, in bankruptcy
or in other appropriate proceedings. ITCES will indemnify LIS for reasonable costs, attorney fees
and/or expenses incurred with respect to a default by ITCES under this Service Agreement.
(d) Cross Default: This Service Agreement is a requirement for
“Interconnection Service” as that term is defined under LIS’s GIA and will be subject to the terms
and conditions of the GIA, including the rights to termination of Interconnection Service.
Notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained in this Service Agreement, a material breach
by LIS of any provision, covenant or other term or condition contained in this Service Agreement
will be considered a breach under LIS’s GIA. An event of default by LIS under Section VII(b) or
by ITCES under Section VII(c) hereof will, after the passage of all applicable notice and cure or
grace periods, be considered a default under this Service Agreement and a default of the LIS’s
GIA. ITCES and LIS will be entitled (but in no event required) in an event of such dual breach or
PUBLIC VERSIONdefault to apply all rights and remedies available in this Service Agreement by reason of a breach
or default.
VIII. INDEMNIFICATION
(a) Indemnity. Each Party will at all times indemnify, defend, and hold the
other Party and its directors, officers, employees, contractors or agents harmless from, any and all
third party damages, losses, claims (including claims and actions relating to injury to or death of
any person or damage to property), demands, suits, recoveries, costs and expenses, court costs,
reasonable attorney fees, and all other obligations by or to third parties, arising out of or resulting
from the other Party’s negligence, willful misconduct, or intentional wrongdoing, except to the
extent of any negligence or intentional wrongdoing by the indemnified Party.
(b) Indemnified Party. If an indemnified Party is entitled to indemnification
under this Article VIII as a result of a claim by a third party, and the Indemnifying Party fails, after
notice and reasonable opportunity to proceed under Section VIII(a), to assume the defense of such
claim, such indemnified Party may, at the expense of the indemnifying Party, contest, settle or
consent to the entry of any judgment with respect to, or pay in full, such claim.
(c) Indemnifying Party. If an indemnifying Party is obligated to indemnify and
hold an indemnified Party harmless under this Article VIII, the amount owing to the indemnified
Party will be the amount of such indemnified Party’s actual loss, net of any insurance or other
recovery.
(d) Reserved.
(e) Indemnity Procedures.
i. Promptly after receipt by an indemnified Party of any claim or notice
of the commencement of any action or administrative or legal
proceeding or investigation as to which the indemnity provided for
in this Article VIII may apply, the indemnified Party will notify the
indemnifying Party of such fact. Any failure of or delay in such
notification will not affect a Party’s indemnification obligation
unless such failure or delay is materially prejudicial to the
indemnifying Party.
ii. The indemnifying Party will have the right to assume the defense
thereof with counsel designated by such indemnifying Party and
reasonably satisfactory to the indemnified Party. If the defendants
in any such action include one or more indemnified Party along with
the indemnifying Party, and the indemnified Party reasonably
concludes that there may be legal defenses available to it which are
different from or additional to those available to the indemnifying
Party, the indemnified Party will have the right to select separate
counsel to assert such legal defenses and to otherwise participate in
the defense of such action on its own behalf.
PUBLIC VERSIONiii. The indemnified Party will be entitled, at its expense, to participate
in any such action, suit or proceeding, the defense of which has been
assumed by the indemnifying Party. Notwithstanding the foregoing,
the indemnifying Party (i) will not be entitled to assume and control
the defense of any such action, suit or proceedings if and to the
extent that, in the reasonable opinion of the indemnified Party and
its counsel, such action, suit or proceeding involves the potential
imposition of criminal liability on the indemnified Party, or there
exists a conflict of interest between the indemnified Party and the
indemnifying Party, in such event the indemnifying Party will pay
the reasonable expenses of the indemnified Party, and (ii) will not
settle or consent to the entry of any judgment in any action, suit or
proceeding without the consent of the indemnified Party, which will
not be unreasonably withheld, conditioned or delayed.
(e) Notwithstanding any other provision of this Service Agreement, the
provisions of this Article VIII are intended to and shall survive termination of this Service
Agreement.
IX. ASSIGNMENT
This Service Agreement will inure to the benefit of and be binding upon each Party’s
successors and permitted assigns. No Party will assign this Service Agreement or their related
contractual rights without the prior written consent of the other Parties, which prior written consent
will not be unreasonably withheld or delayed; provided that the assignee is at least as creditworthy
as the assigning Party and the assignee of LIS will provide ITCES with Security as contemplated
herein; and provided further that LIS will have the right to assign this Service Agreement, without
the consent of ITCES, for collateral security purposes to aid in providing financing for the
generating facilities serviced by the Gen-Tie Facilities under this Agreement, provided that LIS
will promptly notify ITCES of any such assignment. No assignment of this Service Agreement
will release or discharge any Party from their future obligations hereunder unless all such
obligations are assumed by the successor or assignee of that Party in writing.
X. FORCE MAJEURE
Definition of Force Majeure. As used in this Agreement, a “Force Majeure Event” will
mean any act or event that prevents the affected Party from performing its obligations under this
Agreement (other than the payment of money, which may be delayed but not excused) if such act
or event is beyond the reasonable control of and not the fault of the affected Party. A Force
Majeure Event will include, but not be limited to, the following events: war, lightning, earthquake,
fire, volcanic eruption, landslide, raw material shortage (which will be based upon the conditions
set forth in the following paragraph), typhoon, hurricane, flood, tornado, explosion, strikes or
national labor disputes, civil disturbance, act of God or the public enemy, act of terrorism, or action
of a court or public authority (provided that if a claim of Force Majeure Event asserts an
unreasonable delay, action or inaction of a public authority, such delay, action or inaction will only
be a Force Majeure Event if proper and timely application therefore was made, determined as of
the date of such application, taking into account all facts and circumstances after due investigation
PUBLIC VERSIONinto the time required for such requested action, payments of all necessary fees and charges was
made, and diligent and customary pursuit of the application was made).
Exclusions from Definition of Force Majeure Event. Economic hardship alone, if not the
result of another Force Majeure Event, is explicitly excluded from Force Majeure Events and is
solely the responsibility of the affected Party. If either Party is rendered wholly or partially unable
to perform its obligations under this Agreement because of a Force Majeure Event, that Party will
be excused from whatever performance is affected by the Force Majeure Event in accordance with
the terms of this Agreement to the extent so affected, provided that:
i. the affected Party, within ten (10) Business Days after becoming
aware of the occurrence of a Force Majeure Event, gives the other
Party written notice describing the particulars of the occurrence,
including an estimation of its expected duration and probable impact
on the performance of such Party’s obligations, and thereafter
continues to furnish timely regular reports with respect thereto
during the continuation of the Force Majeure Event and the effects
thereof;
ii. the suspension of performance will be of no greater scope and of no
longer duration than is reasonably required by the Force Majeure
Event;
iii. no liability of either Party which arose before the occurrence of the
Force Majeure Event will be excused as a result of the occurrence;
and
iv. the affected Party will exercise all reasonable efforts to mitigate or
limit damages to the other Party.
Upon the occurrence and provision of a proper notice of a Force Majeure Event, the Parties
will negotiate in good faith regarding the continuance of this Agreement or the termination thereof,
which termination will be in accordance with Section IV in the event LIS has elected to terminate
this Service Agreement.
Provided further, and notwithstanding anything to the contrary contained herein, if a Force
Majeure event causes the Gen-Tie Facilities to become physically inoperable (i.e. tornado,
earthquake, etc.), unless otherwise directed by LIS via written notice to ITCES, ITCES will initiate
immediate actions to repair and/or replace all equipment damaged by the above-referenced Force
Majeure event, such expense to be directly charged to and paid by LIS as set forth under Section
V, unless the repairs and/or replacements are greater than $25,000.00. In the event such repairs
involve additional capital investment above $25,000.00 by ITCES, ITCES will subsequently notify
LIS of all necessary repairs and the costs associated therewith pursuant to the provisions contained
within Article V and not initiate the repairs and/or replacements until LIS provides written consent.
Upon consenting to such repairs, LIS will be directly charged and pay to ITCES as set forth under
Section V.
PUBLIC VERSIONXI. Other
(a) Entire Agreement: This Service Agreement represents the entire agreement
between ITCES and LIS for the Construction Work, the O&M Services, and
provision of transmission service by ITCES to LIS via the Gen-Tie Facilities. This
Service Agreement may not be amended, modified, or waived other than by a
written document signed by all Parties.
(b) Confidentiality:
Definition. Confidential Information will include, without limitation, all
information relating to a Party’s technology, research and development, business
affairs, and pricing, and any information supplied by a Party to another Party prior
to the execution of this Service Agreement. Information is Confidential
Information if it is clearly designated or marked in writing as confidential on the
face of the document, or, if the information is conveyed orally or by inspection, if
the Party providing the information orally informs the Party receiving the
information that the information is confidential, or if the information reasonably
ought to be considered as confidential from its nature or from the circumstances
surrounding its disclosure. The Parties will maintain as confidential any
information that is provided and identified by a Party as Critical Energy
Infrastructure Information (“CEII”), as that term is defined in 18 C.F.R. Section
388.113I. Such confidentiality will be maintained in accordance with this Section
XI(b). If requested by the receiving Party, the disclosing Party will provide in
writing, the basis for asserting that the information referred to in this Article
warrants confidential treatment, and the requesting Party may disclose such writing
to the appropriate Governmental Authority. Each Party will be responsible for the
costs associated with affording confidential treatment to its information.
Confidentiality Term. During the term of this Service Agreement, and for a period
of three (3) years after the expiration or termination of this Service Agreement,
except as otherwise provided in this Section XI(b). or with regard to CEII, each
Party will hold in confidence and will not disclose to any person Confidential
Information. CEII will be treated in accordance with Commission policy and
regulations.
Scope. Confidential Information will not include information that the receiving
Party can demonstrate: (1) is generally available to the public other than as a result
of a disclosure by the receiving Party; (2) was in the lawful possession of the
receiving Party on a non-confidential basis before receiving it from the disclosing
Party; (3) was supplied to the receiving Party without restriction by a non-Party,
who, to the knowledge of the receiving Party after due inquiry, was under no
obligation to the disclosing Party to keep such information confidential; (4) was
independently developed by the receiving Party without reference to Confidential
Information of the disclosing Party; (5) is, or becomes, publicly known, through no
wrongful act or omission of the receiving Party or breach of this Service
Agreement; or (6) is required to be disclosed by any Governmental Authority or is
otherwise required to be disclosed by law or subpoena, or is necessary in any legal
PUBLIC VERSIONproceeding establishing rights and obligations under this Service Agreement.
Information designated as Confidential Information will no longer be deemed
confidential if the Party that designated the information as confidential notifies the
receiving Party in writing that it no longer is confidential.
Release of Confidential Information. No Party will release or disclose Confidential
Information to any other person, except to its affiliates, subcontractors, employees,
agents, consultants, or to non-parties who may be or are considering providing
financing to or equity participation with ITC Holdings Corp., ITCES, LIS, or to
potential purchasers or assignees of ITC Holdings Corp., ITCES or LIS, on a needto-
know basis in connection with this Service Agreement, unless such person has
first been advised of the confidentiality provisions of this Section XI(b) and has
agreed in writing to comply with such provisions. Notwithstanding the foregoing,
a Party providing Confidential Information to any person will remain primarily
responsible for any release of Confidential Information in contravention of this
Section XI(b).
Rights. Each Party retains all rights, title, and interest in the Confidential
Information that it discloses to the receiving Party. The disclosure by a Party to the
receiving Party of Confidential Information will not be deemed a waiver by the
disclosing Party or any other person or entity of the right to protect the Confidential
Information from public disclosure.
No Warranties. By providing Confidential Information, no Party makes any
warranties or representations as to its accuracy or completeness. In addition, by
supplying Confidential Information, no Party obligates itself to provide any
particular information or Confidential Information to another Party nor to enter into
any further agreements or proceed with any other relationship or joint venture.
Standard of Care. Each Party will use at least the same standard of care to protect
Confidential Information it receives as it uses to protect its own Confidential
Information from unauthorized disclosure, publication or dissemination, but in no
event less than a reasonable degree of care. Each Party may use Confidential
Information solely to fulfill its obligations to another Party under this Service
Agreement or its regulatory requirements.
Order of Disclosure. If a court or other state or federal agency with government
authority or an entity with the lawful right, power, and apparent authority to do so
requests or requires any Party, by subpoena, oral deposition, interrogatories,
requests for production of documents, administrative order, or otherwise, to
disclose Confidential Information, that Party will provide the disclosing Party with
prompt notice of such request(s) or requirement(s) so that the disclosing Party may
seek an appropriate protective order or waive compliance with the terms of this
Service Agreement. Notwithstanding the absence of a protective order or waiver,
the Party may disclose such Confidential Information which, in the opinion of its
counsel, the Party is legally compelled to disclose. Each Party will use reasonable
efforts to obtain reliable assurance that confidential treatment will be accorded any
Confidential Information so furnished.
Destruction of Confidential Information Upon Termination. Upon termination of
PUBLIC VERSIONthis Service Agreement for any reason, each Party will, within ten (10) calendar
days of receipt of a written request from another Party, destroy, erase, or delete
(with such destruction, erasure, and deletion certified in writing to the requesting

Party, except that the receiving Party may retain archival copies of Confidential

pursuant to receiving Party’s automated archiving or back-up procedures, and so
long as such copies cannot be deleted using commercially reasonable efforts,
provided that the obligation to treat it as Confidential Information in accordance

Remedies. The Parties agree that monetary damages would be inadequate to

XI(b). Each Party accordingly agrees that the disclosing Party will be entitled to

remedy will not be deemed an exclusive remedy for the breach of this Section
XI(b), but will be in addition to all other remedies available at law or in equity. The
Parties further acknowledge and agree that the covenants contained herein are
necessary for the protection of legitimate business interests and are reasonable in
scope. No Party, however, will be liable for indirect, incidental, or consequential
or punitive damages of any nature or kind resulting from or arising in connection
with this Section XI(b).
Disclosure to FERC, its Staff or a State. Notwithstanding anything in this Section
XI(b) to the contrary, if FERC or its staff, during the course of any hearing,
investigation or otherwise, requests information from a Party that is otherwise
required to be maintained in confidence pursuant to this Service Agreement, the
Party will provide the requested information to FERC or its staff, within the time
provided for in the request for information. In providing the information to FERC
or its staff, the Party must, consistent with 18 CFR § 388.112, request that the
information be treated as confidential and non-public by FERC and its staff and
that the information be withheld from public disclosure. The Party will notify the
other Party to this Service Agreement when it is notified by FERC or its staff that
a request to release Confidential Information has been received by FERC, at which
time any of the Parties may respond before such information would be made public,
pursuant to 18 CFR § 388.112. Requests from a state regulatory body conducting
a confidential investigation will be treated in a similar manner if consistent with the
applicable state rules and regulations.
Competitively Sensitive Information. Subject to the exception in the preceding
paragraph of this Section XI(b), any information that a disclosing Party claims is
competitively sensitive, commercial or financial information under this Service
Agreement will not be disclosed by the receiving Party to any person not employed
or retained by the receiving Party, except to the extent disclosure is (i) required by
law; (ii) reasonably deemed by the receiving Party to be required to be disclosed in
connection with a dispute between or among the Parties, or the defense of litigation
PUBLIC VERSIONor dispute; (iii) otherwise permitted by written consent of the disclosing Party, such
consent not to be unreasonably withheld; or (iv) necessary to fulfill its obligations
under this Service Agreement. The Party asserting confidentiality will notify the
receiving Party in writing of the information that Party claims is confidential. Prior
to any disclosures of that Party’s Confidential Information under this subparagraph,
or if any non-party or Governmental Authority makes any request or demand for
any of the information described in this subparagraph, the Party who received the
Confidential Information from the disclosing Party agrees to promptly notify the
disclosing Party in writing and agrees to assert confidentiality and cooperate with
the disclosing Party in seeking to protect the Confidential Information from public
disclosure by confidentiality agreement, protective order or other reasonable
measures.
c. Regulatory Approval: This Service Agreement and its terms will be subject to the

d. Disputes: The Parties shall attempt in good faith to resolve all disputes arising out
